Question 1:

The help file shows that here are 1846 rows and 3 columns. We can also see the same information by using dim() as shown below.

dim(datasaurus_dozen)
[1] 1846    3

The included variables are shown below and identified by using the unique() function

unique(datasaurus_dozen$dataset)
 [1] "dino"       "away"       "h_lines"    "v_lines"    "x_shape"   
 [6] "star"       "high_lines" "dots"       "circle"     "bullseye"  
[11] "slant_up"   "slant_down" "wide_lines"

Question 2

datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset %in% "dino") %>%
  {cor(.$x, .$y)}
[1] -0.06447185
datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset %in% "dino") %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_cor(
    method = "pearson",
    label.x.npc = "left",
    label.y.npc = "top",
    parse = FALSE,
    label.sep = "\n",
    size = 4
  )

Question 3

datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset %in% "star") %>%
  {cor(.$x, .$y)}
[1] -0.0629611
datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset %in% "star") %>%

ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point() +
   stat_cor(
      method = "pearson",
      label.x.npc = "left",
      label.y.npc = "top",
      parse = FALSE,
      label.sep = "\n",
      size = 4
    )

The r value of star is almost identical to that of dino. R of star = -0.063 R of dino = -0.064

Question 5

ggplot(datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = dataset)) +
   stat_cor(
      method = "pearson",
      label.x.npc = "left",
      label.y.npc = "top",
      parse = FALSE,
      label.sep = "\n",
      size = 4
    ) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(x = "", y = "") +
  facet_wrap(~dataset)
